      <div xml:id="NA151-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu iravukkuṟic ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said when [HE] was behind the fence during the night tryst.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA151">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            naṉṉutal pacappiṉum peruntō ṇekiḻiṉuṅ</l>
<l>            koṉmura ṇirumpuli yarumpuḻait tākkic</l>
<l>            cemmaṟuk koṇṭa veṇkōṭ ṭiyāṉai</l>
<l>            kaṉmicai yaruviyiṟ kaḻūuñ cāral</l>
<l>            vāraṟka tilla tōḻi kaṭuvaṉ </l>
<l>            muṟiyār peruṅkiḷai yaṟita lañcik</l>
<l>            kaṟivaḷa raṭukkattiṟ kaḷaviṉiṟ puṇarnta</l>
<l>            cemmuka manti celkuṟi karuṅkāṟ</l>
<l>            poṉṉiṇar vēṅkaip pūñciṉaic celīik</l>
<l>            kuṇṭunīr neṭuñcuṉai nōkkik kaviḻntutaṉ </l>
<l>            puṉṟalaip pāṟumayir tiruttuṅ</l>
<l>            kuṉṟaka nāṭa ṉiravi ṉāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent2">Even if [your] good forehead fades,</l>
<l rend="indent2">even if [your] big shoulders become emaciated,</l>
<l>let him not come at night, friend,</l>
<l rend="indent">on the slope where the elephant washes in the waterfall on stony height,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with [his] white tusk that has taken red stains</l>
<l rend="indent3">since the big tiger had attacked<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tākki</term> can as well be taken with the elephant (in coordination with <term xml:lang="ta">koṇṭa</term>), but I prefer it this way since otherwise <term xml:lang="ta">puli</term> would be an unmarked direct object preceding its subject.</note> [him] in murderous antagonism</l>
<l rend="indent4">on the difficult forest path,</l>
<l>– the man from a land within the hills,</l>
<l>where the red-faced she-monkey, who had united with the male monkey</l>
<l rend="indent">in secret meeting on the pepper-grown mountain side,</l>
<l rend="indent2">fearing that the big horde feeding on sprouts should know,</l>
<l>goes<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">celīi</term>, absolutive, is what is understood by the old commentator (and by T.V.G.), but most mss. read <term xml:lang="ta">celīiyar</term>, infinitive. If we want to stay close to the transmitted text, we should perhaps retain the reading <term xml:lang="ta">neṭuñciṉai</term> in line 10 and read line 8-11 as follows: "where the she-monkey rearranges ... [her] hair, looking [down] from the long branch into the deep water, [thus] completely upturning [it], so that the flowered branch gives way".</note> on a flowering branch of the gold-clustered Vēṅkai tree</l>
<l rend="indent3">with dark trunk [and] fading sign(?),<note place="foot">What is the meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">cel kuṟi</term> here? Does it refer to the tree having been the appointed place of meeting (either for the human or the monkey lovers)?</note></l>
<l>looks upside down into the long mountain pool with deep water,</l>
<l>[and] rearranges the scattered hair on her reddish head.</l>
        </lg>
